flowRoot.flowPara: Often autonomus drones have some sensors capable of determining absolute alititude, such as GPS or distance senosors. These sensors often update at a too slow rate to stablize flight, or they have noisy measurements. A drone will usually also carry accelerometers and gyroscopes for determining attitude, but data form these senosors must be integrated to yield information about position, which leads to severe drifting.
Altitude Control of Simplified Multirotor Drone 160/170

Autonomous multirotors need to perform maneuvers and locate themselves in a three dimensional space. We have developed vertical localisation and control for a simplified multirotor consisting of a rotor on the end of a lever arm equipped with an accelero-meter, gyroscope and proximity sensor. Our implementation is able to stablize the position of the lever within ±1cm of the set point.

text.tspan: [1] M. R. Hermansen, “Position control of simplified tethered drone,” 2013

flowRoot.flowPara: Our work is a continuation of the work done by Hermansen1 in which he managed to stablize the altitude of a simplified, thethered drone by measuring the altitude at 200Hz. Hermansen did, however, not manage to merge frequent samples from accelerometers and infrequent samples from a distance sensor into a usable controller and this is the problem we have solved.
